Below is an extremely fast dead-space segmentation approach that matches what you described and keeps the hot path (compute_all()) lean:

We define an outer envelope inside the bounding box using a single x-sweep:

At each x-interval, take top(x)=max(top_i) and bottom(x)=min(bottom_i) among blocks intersecting that x.

The envelope area is: AreaB = ∫ (top(x) − bottom(x)) dx

Then:

AreaA = bbox_area − AreaB (space between bbox and outer envelope)

If no overlap (or overlap is below a tiny epsilon), union area ≈ sum of block areas (constant), so:

DeadB = AreaB − total_block_area

DeadA = AreaA (by definition envelope excludes that region)

Preventing “tradeoff vs overlap”

To ensure deadspace never fights the overlap constraint:

Compute and use the deadspace only when overlap is essentially zero.

When overlap > eps: set AreaA/AreaB/DeadA/DeadB to 0 (or keep them as bbox defaults), and do not add any deadspace penalty.

This gives you a “two-phase” behavior: first remove overlap, then compact.

